<HEADLINE>
<P>
IRRELEVANTLY OUTFITTED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the midst of the present political and social changes this country is going 
through, I feel (and I would assume the majority of the people not involved in 
the hoopla surrounding the inauguration also feel) that who wears what to which 
function has absolutely no relevance to events and problems in the real world 
and indeed the outfits (and perhaps their wearers) will be forgotten in the 
not-too-distant future. 
</P>
<P>
It is with this idea that I skimmed your article in the View section ("The 
Great Gown Dust-Up," by Bettijane Levine, Jan. 20), and I expended that much 
effort having first seen the inauguration earlier in the day on television and 
feeling that Mrs. Quayle's attire was rather forgettable except for the hat, 
which made the entire package unattractive. Marilyn Quayle, you're no Jackie 
Kennedy. 
</P>
<P>
L. SCOTT HERMAN 
</P>
<P>
Pasadena 
</P>
</TEXT>
