<P>
THE WORLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto's Pakistan People's Party suffered a setback in 
special parliamentary elections in Punjab province but gained ground in two 
others. About 3 million voters were electing national and provincial lawmakers 
in what was seen as the first test of public opinion on the two-month-old 
government of Bhutto. The results did not alter the balance of power in the 
National Assembly, the lower house of Parliament, where the Pakistan People's 
Party won 124 seats in an election last November. In Punjab, where the rival 
Islamic Democratic Alliance is already in power, Bhutto's party took only two 
of nine seats. But overall it gained 11 of the 20 seats being contested. 
</P>
