<TEXT>
<P>
Nearly 3,000 Soviet children will be tested for AIDS because of the infection 
of at least 27 infants and four mothers while being treated at a Moscow-area 
hospital, the newspaper Komsomolskaya Pravda said. Authorities suspect poor 
sanitary conditions and the possible reuse of disposable syringes. The paper 
also quoted Vladimir Pokrovsky, head of a special AIDS research laboratory, as 
saying that acquired immune deficiency syndrome is spreading in the Soviet 
Union, where the public is generally indifferent to the deadly disease. "The 
epidemic has entered our country," Pokrovsky said. "It is gathering speed, and 
we now have 146 virus carriers." 
</P>
