<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Olympian Mike Holland defended his 90-meter title at the U.S. Ski Jumping 
Championships, shortened to one round because of erratic winds at Lake Placid, 
N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
Holland, of Norwich, Vt., jumped 114.5 meters in the first round on the Olympic 
hill, but fell after going 123 meters on his second try. Officials called for a 
delay, then ended the meet when wind conditions did not change. 
</P>
<P>
Holland won with 112.0 points to 103.5 for Tad Langlois of Newport, N.H., who 
jumped 109 meters. Mark Konopacke of Kingsford, Mich., was third, jumping 109 
meters for 102.5 points. 
</P>
