<HEADLINE>
<P>
2 CRITICALLY INJURED BY BLAST AT HOME 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An explosion apparently caused by a gas leak destroyed a Pacific Beach 
apartment Saturday morning and critically injured two residents, a Fire 
Department spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
Firefighters responded to the two-story complex in the 900 block of Tourmaline 
Street shortly after 5 a.m. and found two residents lying in the front yard, 
Capt. Bob Landis said. 
</P>
<P>
The victims, Larry Harlin, age not given, and Deborah Arnaudo, 24, were taken 
to UC San Diego Medical Center, Landis said. Harlin suffered burns over 85% of 
his body, and Arnaudo suffered burns over almost 45% of her body. Both were in 
critical condition Saturday afternoon, a hospital spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
Fire investigators suspect that the explosion, which blew out a first floor 
wall, occurred when natural gas leaking in a bedroom closet was ignited by an 
open flame. 
</P>
<P>
The explosion caused $12,500 in damages, Landis said. 
</P>
